#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:2
msgid "Supplementing custom rosdep keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:6
msgid "Contents"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:9
msgid "Overview and motivation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:11
msgid ""
"As explained in :doc:`../Intermediate/Rosdep`, ``rosdep`` looks for rosdep "
"keys in ``package.xml`` files and maps them to packages to be installed for "
"the ROS distribution and OS in use. Anyone can request for new rosdep keys "
"to be added by `contributing to rosdistro <https://github.com/ros/rosdistro/"
"blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#rosdep-rules-contributions>`_. This is the "
"preferred course of action when you have some dependency (like a ``apt`` or "
"``pip`` package) that you wish to be able to install via ``rosdep``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:15
msgid ""
"However, there are many cases when contributing your keys directly might be "
"difficult. For example, if the dependency"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:18
msgid ""
"is not available on the target distributions default APT (or pip) "
"repositories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:19
msgid "is a proprietary library"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:20
msgid "is some niche library which is useful only for you or your organization"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:21
msgid ""
"is a ROS package you :doc:`built and packaged yourself <../../How-To-Guides/"
"Building-a-Custom-Deb-Package>`, but don't wish to share with the broader "
"ROS community"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:23
msgid ""
"While the option exists to :doc:`fork rosdistro <../../How-To-Guides/Using-"
"Custom-Rosdistro>` in its entirety, this might be overkill if you just want "
"to keep using a official ROS distribution as usual, only with some extra "
"rosdep keys defined on top. This tutorial explains how to achieve this."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:26
msgid ""
"As a word of warning though, please don't use this indiscriminately. It can "
"cause very hard to debug problems because of binary incompatibilities which "
"can manifest in silent failures, unexplained crashes, or data corruption. "
"And if you're asking anyone for help on a system with this enabled, make "
"sure to explain everything that's being added or overridden."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:31
msgid "Preliminaries: How ``rosdep`` fetches rosdep keys"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:33
msgid ""
"In order to get a good understanding of what we're about to do, let's first "
"explore some relevant details about how ``rosdep`` works."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:35
msgid ""
"``rosdep`` is similar to other tools like ``apt`` that use a sources list to "
"maintain a local index. These sources are stored in ``/etc/ros/rosdep/"
"sources.list.d``. This is similar to how apt stores repositories in ``/etc/"
"apt/sources.list.d``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:39
msgid ""
"By default (as part of first-time setup, ``rosdep init``), you only have a "
"single sources file: ``/etc/ros/rosdep/sources.list.d/20-default.list``. "
"Inspecting its contents, you will see entries like these:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:42
msgid ""
"$ cat /etc/ros/rosdep/sources.list.d/20-default.list\n"
"...\n"
"yaml https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ros/rosdistro/master/rosdep/base."
"yaml\n"
"yaml https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ros/rosdistro/master/rosdep/python."
"yaml\n"
"..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:50
msgid ""
"These entries are what dictates where ``rosdep`` fetches rosdep keys and "
"their mappings (rosdep **rules**) from when ``rosdep update`` is called. "
"When called, ``rosdep`` compiles the relevant contents from all declared "
"entries in all sources files into a local cached index. This local index is "
"then used when installing or looking up (\"resolving\") rosdep keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:54
msgid ""
"For example, the fact that the first entry (``base.yaml``) defines the "
"``libopencv-dev`` key (see `here <https://github.com/ros/rosdistro/"
"blob/72f24d6/rosdep/base.yaml#L5240-L5252>`_) is what allows ``rosdep`` to "
"resolve it:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:56
msgid ""
"$ rosdep where-defined libopencv-dev\n"
"https://raw.githubusercontent.com/ros/rosdistro/master/rosdep/base.yaml\n"
"$ rosdep resolve libopencv-dev\n"
"#apt\n"
"libopencv-dev"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:64
msgid ""
"In summary, it allows ``rosdep`` to resolve the ``libopencv-dev`` key to the "
"``apt`` package of the same name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:66
msgid ""
"Note that, from the output above, we can deduce that the command was run on "
"a Ubuntu or Debian OS. On RHEL, the key instead resolves to the DNF package "
"``opencv-devel``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:69
msgid ""
"$ rosdep resolve libopencv-dev --os=rhel:9\n"
"#dnf\n"
"opencv-devel"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:76
msgid "Extending ``rosdep`` with a custom sources file"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:78
msgid ""
"The above hopefully makes it clear what needs to be done to get ``rosdep`` "
"to understand new keys: add a new custom sources file!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:80
msgid ""
"As a toy example, let's add a new sources file telling ``rosdep`` to fetch "
"keys from a YAML file stored on the local machine. Fire up your favorite "
"text editor and write the following into ``/etc/ros/rosdep/sources.list.d/30-"
"custom.list`` (the editor will need to be launched with root privileges, e."
"g. via ``sudo``):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:83
msgid "yaml file:///etc/ros/rosdep/custom_rules.yaml"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:87
msgid "Now write the following into ``/etc/ros/rosdep/custom_rules.yaml``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:89
msgid ""
"awesome_library:\n"
"  ubuntu: [awesome_library]\n"
"that_other_library:\n"
"  ubuntu:\n"
"    pip:\n"
"      packages: [another_library]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:98
msgid "This defines two new rosdep rules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:100
msgid ""
"The key ``awesome_library``, defined only for Ubuntu, mapping to the ``apt`` "
"package of the same name"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:101
msgid ""
"The key ``that_other_library``, defined only for Ubuntu, mapping to the "
"``pip`` package named ``another_library``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:103
msgid ""
"After running ``rosdep update``, ``rosdep`` will detect the new ``30-custom."
"list``, prompting it to scan the contents of the ``custom_rules.yaml`` file. "
"Now ``rosdep`` is set up to recognize these new keys and what they should "
"map to:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:106
msgid ""
"$ rosdep resolve awesome_library\n"
"#apt\n"
"awesome_library\n"
"$ rosdep resolve that_other_library\n"
"#pip\n"
"another_library"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:115
msgid ""
"Now all you have to do is add ``<depend>awesome_library</depend>`` to your "
"ROS packages ``package.xml``, and ``rosdep`` will know how to install the "
"dependency!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:118
msgid "Closing remarks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:120
msgid ""
"The toy example above only hints at what is possible with custom rosdep keys."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:122
msgid ""
"**Is your dependency an APT package hosted in a third party PPA?** Not a "
"problem. Since all ``rosdep`` does is converting the key to a ``apt "
"install`` invocation, APT will have no problem installing the package "
"(provided you have added the PPA)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:125
msgid ""
"**Is your dependency a pip package hosted in a third party index?** Add the "
"index to your ``pip.conf`` and you're good to go."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:127
msgid ""
"**Sources files don't have to point to files on the local machine.** Both "
"``file://`` and ``https://`` syntax is supported (on Linux, absolute paths "
"start with ``/``, which leads to a triple slash like ``file:///etc/rosdep/my."
"file``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:129
msgid ""
"**Sources are loaded in alphabetical order.** If you add a conflicting rule "
"in the 30 prefix it will not be used. If you created a sources file with a "
"10 prefix it will override packages in the default list (prefix 20). If "
"you're using packages installed from binary repositories it's highly "
"recommended to not override dependency declarations as it will likely cause "
"binary incompatibilities which can be very hard to debug."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/Tutorials/Advanced/Supplementing-Custom-Rosdep-Keys.rst:133
msgid ""
"**Merging keys is not possible.** It is not possible to e.g. only add a "
"``fedora`` installation rule to an existing rosdep key. Depending on the "
"load order, such rule would either be ignored, or it would completely "
"override the whole rosdep key, removing all other installers."
msgstr ""

